<subSubSection id="1CDF5F80FFBEFFE46DC2FDBBFD20A992" pageId="26" pageNumber="1539" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="547A0C0BFFBEFFE46DC2FDBBFD20A992" blockId="26.[178,1085,550,656]" pageId="26" pageNumber="1539">
Diagnosis: Within 
<taxonomicName id="93C57788FFBEFFE46CB9FDBBFDFDA93E" authority="SPINOLA" authorityName="SPINOLA" box="[457,616,550,572]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="1539" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Platynopterinae">Platynopterinae</taxonomicName>
only in members of 
<taxonomicName id="93C57788FFBEFFE46E3DFDBBFC3DA939" authorityName="OPITZ" authorityYear="1997" box="[845,936,550,571]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Pilosirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="1555" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="66B1D019FFBEFFE46E3DFDBBFC3DA939" box="[845,936,550,571]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="1539">Pilosirus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="CCFE108EFFBEFFE46EC9FDBBFB93A93E" box="[953,1030,550,572]" captionStart="Figs 70-80" captionStartId="21.[178,218,1351,1373]" captionTargetBox="[178,1100,235,1309]" captionTargetId="figure-1@21.[178,1100,212,1333]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Figs 70-80: Antennae. (70) Isoforma fritilla, female; (71) I. goryi, female; (72) Isoforma planata, female; (73) Pilosirus brunoi, male; (74) Isoforma subgilva, female; (75) Pilosirus amazonicus, female; (76) P. fasciatus, female; (77) Platynoptera carti, male; (78) P. flavohumeralis, male; (79) P. humeralis, male; (80) P. lyciformis, male." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5294864" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5294864/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="1539">Fig. 73</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="93C57788FFBEFFE46DC2FDDFFEBAA955" authorityName="OPITZ" authorityYear="2015" box="[178,303,578,599]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Ambonoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="1555" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="66B1D019FFBEFFE46DC2FDDFFEBAA955" box="[178,303,578,599]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="1539">Ambonoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="CCFE108EFFBEFFE46C31FDDFFE1AA95A" box="[321,399,578,600]" captionStart="Figs 62-69" captionStartId="20.[178,218,1390,1412]" captionTargetBox="[203,1054,249,1347]" captionTargetId="figure-1@20.[178,1066,212,1373]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Figs 62-69: Antennae. (62) Ambonoides retinoides, male; (63) A. caraguata, female; (64) Artoadenus dius, male; (65) A. regina, male; (66) Aspitonis alarutinis, male; (67) A. graminis, female; (68) A. undulicornis, male; (69) Isoforma biguttula, male." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5294862" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5294862/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="1539">Fig. 62</figureCitation>
) is the 7 
<superScript id="A3B0A143FFBEFFE46C81FDA1FE68A948" attach="left" box="[497,509,572,586]" fontSize="6" pageId="26" pageNumber="1539">th</superScript>
antennomere disproportionally large. But, in 
<taxonomicName id="93C57788FFBEFFE46E92FDDFFBA8A955" authorityName="OPITZ" authorityYear="1997" box="[994,1085,578,599]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Pilosirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="1555" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="66B1D019FFBEFFE46E92FDDFFBA8A955" box="[994,1085,578,599]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="1539">Pilosirus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens the pronotal disc is evenly convex whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="93C57788FFBEFFE46E52FDC3FC0AA971" authorityName="OPITZ" authorityYear="2015" box="[802,927,606,627]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Ambonoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="1555" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="66B1D019FFBEFFE46E52FDC3FC0AA971" box="[802,927,606,627]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="1539">Ambonoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens the pronotal disc is up-curved and flanged at the sides.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1CDF5F80FFBEFFE46DC2FD02FE79A9D0" pageId="26" pageNumber="1539" type="description">
<paragraph id="547A0C0BFFBEFFE46DC2FD02FE79A9D0" blockId="26.[178,1084,671,722]" pageId="26" pageNumber="1539">
